tasks.description:
Extract the on/off decision into a pure, unit-testable helper used by BOTH discovery (initial status) and the manager (which list to mutate on toggle). This keeps the logic DRY and isolated.

Create `apps/server/src/services/extensions/extension-enable-resolution.ts` with these exports:

```typescript
interface CoreExtensionInfo {
  id: string;
  defaultEnabled: boolean;
  canDisable: boolean;
}
interface ExtensionsConfig {
  enabled: string[];
  disabled: string[];
}

/** True when an extension's baseline (pre-override) state is ON. */
function defaultsOn(id: string, core: Map<string, CoreExtensionInfo>): boolean {
  const info = core.get(id);
  return info ? info.defaultEnabled : false; // user extensions default off
}

/** Resolve whether an extension should be enabled, given config overrides. */
function isEnabled(
  id: string,
  config: ExtensionsConfig,
  core: Map<string, CoreExtensionInfo>
): boolean {
  return defaultsOn(id, core)
    ? !config.disabled.includes(id) // default-on: off only if explicitly disabled
    : config.enabled.includes(id); // default-off: on only if explicitly enabled
}
```

Also add a `setEnabled(id, on, config, core)` helper that returns the NEXT `{ enabled, disabled }` config based on the toggle-routing rule (the lists capture deviations, so the helper dictates which list to mutate):

| Extension | Default | Enable action | Disable action |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| default-on core (Dork Hub) | on | remove id from `disabled` | add id to `disabled` |
| default-off core (Hello World, Linear Loop) | off | add id to `enabled` | remove id from `enabled` |
| user / marketplace | off | add id to `enabled` | remove id from `enabled` |

So `setEnabled` logic: if `defaultsOn(id, core)` â†’ on=remove id from `disabled`, off=add id to `disabled`; else â†’ on=add id to `enabled`, off=remove id from `enabled`. Always return a NEW `{ enabled, disabled }` object (no mutation of the input); dedupe so an id is never added twice.

Export `CoreExtensionInfo`, `ExtensionsConfig`, `defaultsOn`, `isEnabled`, `setEnabled`. The `CoreExtensionInfo` type defined here is the canonical one consumed by `ensureCoreExtensions()` (task 1.2 should import it from here once this lands) and the manager.

Tests â€” new `apps/server/src/services/extensions/__tests__/extension-enable-resolution.test.ts`:
- default-on baseline: core ext with `defaultEnabled:true`, absent from both lists â†’ `isEnabled` true.
- default-off baseline: core ext with `defaultEnabled:false`, absent â†’ false; user ext (not in core map), absent â†’ false.
- All six enable/disableâ†’list-mutation cases from the table (default-on enable/disable; default-off-core enable/disable; user enable/disable).
- "new core extension on upgrade": a freshly-shipped core id absent from both `enabled` and `disabled` â†’ resolves to its `defaultEnabled` (on for default-on, off for default-off).
- default-off-core opt-in path: add to `enabled` â†’ `isEnabled` true.
- `setEnabled` returns new objects without mutating input; no duplicate ids.

Acceptance criteria:
- [ ] `extension-enable-resolution.ts` exports `CoreExtensionInfo`, `ExtensionsConfig`, `defaultsOn`, `isEnabled`, `setEnabled` as pure functions (no I/O, no config-manager imports).
- [ ] `extension-enable-resolution.test.ts` covers default-on/off baselines, all six toggleâ†’list cases, new-core-on-upgrade, and default-off opt-in.
- [ ] `pnpm test -- --run` passes (heed `reference_vitest_dev_env_gotcha`; build packages before bare vitest).
